{"cursor":"24412","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n extended-vision caboose at the end of a train in 1993]] A 'caboose' is a manned\n American rail transport vehicle coupled at the end of a freight train.\n\nCabooses were once used on nearly every freight train. Until the 1980s, laws in\nthe United States and Canada required all freight trains to have a caboose and a\nfull crew, for safety. Technology eventually advanced such that the railroads,\nin an effort to save money and reduce crew members, stated that a caboose was\nunnecessary and their use has since declined; they are seldom seen on trains,\nexcept on locals and smaller railroads.\n","linknr":350,"url":"Caboose","recorded":1362554012,"links":37,"instances":["ship","kitchen","transportation","rail","california","us"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Rolling stock","Rolling stock of Canada","Rolling stock of the United States","Freight equipment"],"headings":["Function","History","Caboose types","Etymology","Preservation and reuse of cabooses","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/BN_caboose%2C_Eola_Yard%2C_1993.jpg/300px-BN_caboose%2C_Eola_Yard%2C_1993.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Caboose_interior.jpg/220px-Caboose_interior.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/FRED_cropped.jpg/220px-FRED_cropped.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Cupola_caboose.jpg/220px-Cupola_caboose.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/CabooseInteriorSRM.jpg/170px-CabooseInteriorSRM.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/